  "title": "لاَ النَّافِيَة لِلْجِنْس",
  "titleEn": "Absolute Negation",
  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Lā al-Nāfiya lil-Jins (لا النافية للجنس)",
      "titleArabic": "لا النافية للجنس",
      "content": [
        "This لا negates the entire genus or category of something, expressing absolute negation. Its ism (subject) is in the accusative without tanwīn when it's a single indefinite noun."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Negates the entire category/genus",
        "Ism is manṣūb without tanwīn (if single)",
        "Used in famous phrases: لَا إِلَهَ إِلَّا اللهُ",
        "Different from لَا used for simple negation"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "لَا إِلَهَ إِلَّا اللهُ", "english": "There is no god except Allah" },
        { "arabic": "لَا شَكَّ فِي ذَلِكَ", "english": "There is no doubt in that" },
        { "arabic": "لَا رَيْبَ فِيهِ", "english": "There is no doubt in it" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Hamzat al-Istifhām (همزة الاستفهام)",
      "titleArabic": "همزة الاستفهام",
      "content": [
        "The interrogative hamza (أَ) is used to form yes/no questions. It can be used with positive or negative statements to form different types of questions."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "أَ can be followed by أَمْ for alternative questions",
        "أَلَيْسَ = Is it not? (rhetorical)",
        "Can precede any part of speech",
        "Often implies expectation of affirmative answer"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "أَذَهَبَ مُحَمَّدٌ؟", "english": "Did Muhammad go?" },
        { "arabic": "أَلَيْسَ هَذَا صَحِيحًا؟", "english": "Is this not correct?" }
      ]
    }
  ],
